eb551fc2-d5ae-4eb7-a86f-9d3bf81ced9b.3a9080b8-c0d6-472c-8d7c-d435c5365cfb.prompt=Enter Server Hostname to Perform Health Check\: eb551fc2-d5ae-4eb7-a86f-9d3bf81ced9b.6274b060-192d-4af7-9080-4fece4ffa9b1.description=
This operation is used to send a smtp email.
 
Inputs\:
    hostname - The hostname or ip address of the smtp server.
    port - The port smtp service is listening.
    from - From email address.
    to - A delimiter separated list of email address(es) or recipients.
    cc - A delimiter separated list of email address(es) or recipients, to be placed in the CC.
    bcc - A delimiter separated list of email address(es) or recipients, to be placed in the BCC.
    subject - The email subject. If a subject spans on multiple lines, it is formatted to a single one.
    body - The body of the email.
    htmlEmail - The value should be true if the email is in rich text/html format. The value should be false if the email is in plain text format.
Valid values\: true, false. 
Default value\: true. 
    readReceipt - The value should be true if read receipt is required, else false. 
Valid values\: true, false. 
Default value\: false. 
    attachments - A delimiter separated list of files to attach (must be full path).
    headers - This input contains extra headers you want to be added in the mail. The input has a 'Map' format. Header names are separated from header values through a column delimiter and headers will be separated between them by a row delimiter.
Example\:
    Sensitivity\:Company-Confidential
    message-type\:Multiple Part
    Sensitivity\:Personal
In the above example, the columnDelimiter is "\:" and the rowDelimiter is the new line. You can define multiple values for the same header like in the example above. The delimiters can have multiple characters, but be careful that the rowDelimiter is not a substring of the columnDelimiter.
    rowDelimiter - The delimiter that separates headers in the 'headers' input.
Default value\: "\:"
Examples\: '|', '\='
    columnDelimiter - The delimiter that separates the header name from header value on the same row.
Default value\: "\n"	
Examples\: ';', '\#'
    username - If SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send.
    password - If SMTP authentication is needed, the password to use.
    characterSet - The character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16, UTF-32, EUC-JP, ISO-2022-JP, Shift_JIS, Windows-31J.
Default value\: UTF-8.
    contentTransferEncoding - The content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. 
Valid values\: quoted-printable, base64, 7bit, 8bit, binary, x-token.
Default value\: quoted-printable (or Q Encoding).
    delimiter - A delimiter to separate the email recipients and the attachments.
Default value\: ','
    encryptionKeystore - The path to the pks12 formatted keystore used to encrypt the mail.
    encryptionKeyAlias - The alias of a RSA key pair from the encryptionKeystore. The public key from the pair will be used to encrypt the mail. The key pair must not have password. The recommended key size is 2048 bit or higher.
    encryptionKeystorePassword - The password for the encryptionKeystore.
    encryptionAlgorithm - The encryption algorithm applied on the key from the keystore in order to encypt email parts. 
Default value\: AES256_CBC.
Valid values\: DES_EDE3_CBC, RC2_CBC, IDEA_CBC, CAST5_CBC, AES128_CBC, AES192_CBC, AES256_CBC, CAMELLIA128_CBC, CAMELLIA192_CBC, CAMELLIA256_CBC, SEED_CBC, DES_EDE3_WRAP, AES128_WRAP, AES256_WRAP, CAMELLIA128_WRAP, CAMELLIA192_WRAP, CAMELLIA256_WRAP, SEED_WRAP.
    enableTLS - Enables starttls. If the server supports TLS or SSL, the communications will be secured by TLS or SSL. If it doesn't support TLS or SSL the communication will be unsecure.
Valid values\: true, false. 
Default value\: false.
    timeout - The timeout in seconds for sending the mail message.

Responses\:
    success - Successfully sent the email.
    failure - Failed to send the email.

Note\:
1. For special characters (East Asian, right-to-left languages, etc.) you must install the support files on your local machine.
2. For doing this on Windows go to Control Panel -> Regional and Language Options -> Language and check the options at Supplemental language support.
3. You can use KeyStore Explorer to obtain RSA Keystore with keyPairs for encryption/decryption.
    3.1 If you get "llegal key size exception" you don't have JCE Unlimited Strength installed.
eb551fc2-d5ae-4eb7-a86f-9d3bf81ced9b.69f85e29-bd74-499b-8c33-f65e1de42193.description=
This flow detects the operating system of a given host, performs a health check on the host and creates a report with information retrieved by the health check. If a host is not supplied, it will run on localhost.

If enableLogging is true, the log file created with the logging mechanism is created on localhost, if the flow is run locally, or on the corresponding ras if the flow is executed remotely.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname or IP address of the system to perform the health check on.
    username - The user to connect to the host.
    password - The password to connect to the host.
    reportLocation - The absolute path for the report. The generated report is an html file. If the flow fails the report will not be generated.
Example\: C\:\reports\executionReport.html
    diskName - The disk name (Device) to check, for the linux version. For windows machines this input will be ignored.
Default value\: /dev/sda
    enableLogging - The option to create a log file with information about the execution of the flow. By default logging is disabled. If this option is set to true but the initialization of the log fails, then logging will be disabled.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    logLocation - The absolute path where the log file will be created/updated. This is a required input if 'enableLogging' is true. If you don't supply it, you will be prompted. If the directory supplied does not exist, it will be created.
Example\: C\:\execution.log
    loggingLevel - The level of detail information will be present in the log file. If TRACE is used, then no error messages will be logged. This input is case sensitive.
Valid values\: TRACE, DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR, FATAL.
Default value\: DEBUG.

Responses\:
    success - The health check completed successfully.
    failure - An error occurred during the detection of the operating system of the specified host or during the health check of that host.

Results\:
    osName - This is the primary output. This result contains the result of the detection of the operating system for the specified host.
    exception - This result contains information about the cause of the failure.
eb551fc2-d5ae-4eb7-a86f-9d3bf81ced9b.f2edbb1a-8ea1-42f8-9f96-5530f423e7bd.description=This flow is used to Create Changes. Inputs host - The URL of the ServiceNow instance. Format\: scheme\://domain Example\: https\://dev10000.service-now.com authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. Default value\: basic Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, anonymous, "" or a list of valid values separated by comma. Example\: basic | basic,digest username - The ServiceNow username used to perform the request. password - The ServiceNow password used to perform the request. apiVersion - The API version with which the request will be sent. The call will be made using the latest API version when this input is left empty. Example\: v1 requestBody - The string to include in the body of the request, in the format accepted by ServiceNow. In case more Change fields need to be addressed, they can be provided in the "requestBody" input. When a custom body is provided, the values provided in the inputs named "change" will be ignored unless their reference is used in the new body. Example\: {'short_description'\:'Example description','severity'\:'1','assigned_to'\:'46c1293aa9fe1981000dc753e75ebeee','state'\:'4'} changeShortDescription - The short description of the Change to be created, in the form of a string. If this input is left empty, the short description of the created Change will be empty. changeDescription - The description of the Change to be created, in the form of a string. If this input is left empty, description of the created Change will be empty. changeNumber - The number of the Change to be created. Should contain the "CHG" prefix followed by 7 or more digits. If this input is left empty, ServiceNow will automatically assign a number. Example\: CHG0100001 changeRequestedBy - The system ID of the entity that requested the Change. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 changeCategory - The Category name in the form of a string. Example\: Software, Hardware changeConfigurationItem - The system ID of the Configuration Item. (CMDB CI) Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 changePriority - The Priority of the Change, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 5. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 changeRisk - The risk of the Change, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 5. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 changeImpact - The impact of the Change, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 changeApproval - The Approval status in the form of a string. Valid values\: approved, requested, not requested yet, rejected changeType - The type of the Change in the form of a string. Example\: Routine, Comprehensive changeState - The State of the Change, in the form of a positive integer. Each integer represents an Change State as follows\: 1\=Open, 2\=Work in Progress, 3\=Closed Complete, 4\=Closed Incomplete, 7\=Closed Skipped. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 7 changeAssignmentGroup - The system ID of the Assignment Group. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 changeAssignedTo - The system ID of the entity to which the Change should be assigned to. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 preemptiveAuth - If this field is "true", authentication info will be sent in the first request. If this is "false" a request with no authentication info will be made and if the server responds with 401 and a header such as WWW-Authenticate\: Basic realm\="myRealm", only then will the authentication info be sent. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site. proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default value\: 8080. Valid values\: -1, and positive integer values. When the value is '-1' the default port of the scheme, specified in the 'proxyHost', will be used. proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy. proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value. trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL/TSL. A certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it. Default value\: false Valid values\: true, false x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker (Man-In-The-Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option. Default value\: strict Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all trustKeystore - The pathname of the Java TrustStore file. This contains certificates from other parties that you expect to communicate with, or from Certificate Authorities that you trust to identify other parties. If the protocol (specified by the URL) is not HTTPS or if trustAllRoots is "true" this input is ignored. Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS) trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied. Default value\: changeit connectTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A timeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds Examples\: 10, 20 socketTimeout - The timeout for waiting for data (a maximum period inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A socketTimeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls in a serializable session object therefore they will be available on a branch level (same subflow, same lane). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false keepAlive - Specifies whether to create a shared connection that will be used in subsequent calls. If keepAlive is false, the already open connection will be used and after execution it will close it. The operation will use a connection pool stored in a GlobalSessionObject that will be available throughout the execution (the flow and subflows, between parallel split lanes). Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false connectionsMaxPerRoute - The maximum limit of connections on a per route basis. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections per given route. Default value\: 2 connectionsMaxTotal - The maximum limit of connections in total. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections in total. Default value\: 20 headers - The list containing the headers to use for the request separated by new line (CRLF).The header name - value pair will be separated by "\:". Format\: According to HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). Examples\: Accept\:text/plain responseCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP response. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS. Default value\: ISO-8859-1 followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects. Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false requestCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP request body. If contentType is empty, the requestCharacterSet will use the default value. If contentType will include charset (ex.\: "application/json; charset\=UTF-8"), the requestCharacterSet value will overwrite the charset value from contentType input. This should not be provided for method\=GET, HEAD, TRACE Default value\: ISO-8859-1 Results\: returnResult - This will contain the response entity. In case of an error this output will contain the error message. document - This will contain the response body. exception - In case of success response, this result is empty. In case of failure response, this result contains the java stack trace of the runtime exception. statusCode - The HTTP status code. Format\: 1xx (Informational - Request received, continuing process), 2xx (Success - The action was successfully received, understood, and accepted), 3xx (Redirection - Further action must be taken in order to complete the request), 4xx (Client Error - The request contains bad syntax or cannot be fulfilled), 5xx Server Error - The server failed to fulfil an apparently valid request) Examples\: 200, 404 responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by newline. Format\: This is conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). systemId - The system ID of the created Change. Responses success - The operation completed without a runtime exception. failure - A runtime exception occurred. This may be due to incorrectly formated inputs (headers, proxy, queryParams, url). Notes\: 1. The reference of the "change" inputs should be removed from inside the "requestBody" input when they are deleted. 2. When more Change fields are required, than the ones exposed, you can add them as inputs and insert their reference in the Json found in the "requestBody" input. 3. In order to authenticate using an OAuth token\: 3.1. The headers input should contain the following header\: Authorization\:Bearer 3.2. The username and password inputs should remain empty. eb551fc2-d5ae-4eb7-a86f-9d3bf81ced9b.f462ad7a-4857-460b-8418-7ed07f6e3b56.prompt=Enter Email Address to send Report To\:
